“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

🎞 by @wagatwe 💕 “A TikTok follower asked me to list the different types of feminisms. There’s no way I could do that, so I wanted to give a little #feminism101: what all feminisms have in common, how different ones are created, and why different labels *can* be helpful (even if they aren’t always).

I use Black feminism as a compass for my antirape work, but I still integrate other disciplines into my work: trauma theory, psychoanalytic theory, sociology...the list goes on!

Ultimately, it’s a way to combat ahistoricism by learning from great Black women before me, honoring their contributions to feminism, and building on their legacy.” (Posted with consent) 

#Blackfeminism #womanism #feministtheory #criticaltheory

There is no marriage equality until people with disabilities can marry without losing benefits. 💭 by #FeministPartner @liberaljane ✨ “People with disabilities should have the right to marry without losing their income, benefits, or health insurance.

⭐️ In many countries, including the United States, Canada, and the United Kingdom, people with disabilities are discouraged from getting married or are pushed to divorce in order to get or maintain their income, benefits, and health insurance. 

📍 In the United States specifically, it's because benefits such as Supplemental Security Income (SSI) and Medicaid are needs-based and focus on current assets and income. When someone marries someone not in those programs, their partner's assets and income are combined with theirs. It is because of the combined income that many married people with disabilities lose their SSI and Medicaid benefits. For people with disabilities who are already married, many have been forced to divorce and live separately in order to keep benefits that they need to survive. 

⭐️ People with disabilities shouldn't be forced to choose between the benefits they need to survive and their partners. 🌙”

[Digital illustration of a woman with brown skin and curly black hair. She is disabled and is sitting in a grey wheelchair looking at the viewer. The woman is wearing a cream color linen dress, pink and blue flower print go-go boots, pink and blue pom pom earrings. There's a text bubble that reads, ' people with disabilities STILL do not have marriage equality']

Our art curator @amandabjorn interviewed @hanneke_van_leeuwen for this week’s #FeministArtFeature series. Hanneke van Leeuwen is a photographer and visual artist based in Amsterdam, the Netherlands. See more on @art.feminist 

Can you share something you've learned from creating this body of work that would resonate with our community? 

 ‘What is a female body? I’m female but I’ve never seen my body as a female body. I see it as my body. The suit I was born in. I’ve always felt so much pressure to be something because of those words ‘female body’; to be that image or to live up to it. I never quite understood that. My body is mine, it is what it is. I respect it for what it is, in whatever form.”

node.text:
✍️ by @morganharpernichols “5 Words to Keep in Your Vocabulary 
(even when you’re faced with unknowns)”

“Rest

The act of ceasing to work in order to be refreshed and recover your strength (even when you don’t think you’re worthy of it)

Play

To engage in an activity just for the fun of it (even when there’s no definitive factor of why it’s important or how it’s productive)

Curiosity 

A stirring desire to look around right where you are to learn something new (even when there are unknowns ahead of you)

Dream

A cherished thought of something you would like to happen (that even when it seems too childish or impractical, you can still recognize the act of dreaming itself as something that keeps hope stirring within you).

Grace

Grace is unmerited favor giving you permission to see who you are beyond what you do. Grace is the sun that rises yet another day (even as you wait for other things to fall in place).”

MHN (posted with consent)

🪧 by @thefemalewarhol “Letting go is not a linear process. Sometimes, it’ll feel like you’re taking 10 steps back. Or that the progress you’ve made gets sabotaged by one specific thought or memory. Stop being so hard on yourself. 

You’re going to think about them, many times. You’re going to romanticize and have make believe conversations with yourself. You’re going to wish the outcome was different. You’re gonna want to reach out, you’re going to downplay the bad and emphasize the good. But the most important part of this whole process is that you stop expecting yourself not to feel. Understand that with time those thoughts, memories and urges become less common. The more you can trust that choosing yourself was the right thing to do, the more you will allow yourself to be human and will see these various attempts as an invitation to heal the unhealed parts of you that once allowed and accepted less.”

Gloria Richardson. Photographs by Leonard McCombe (1963) Via @blackarchives.co 

Today we honor Gloria Richardson, ‘a firebrand civil rights activist who drew national attention in the early 1960s in a showdown on Maryland’s Eastern Shore that presaged the Black Power movement and led to a year-long imposition of martial law. Gloria Richardson passed away on July 15 at her home in Manhattan. She was 99. #HERstory

Recognized as a major figure in the Civil Rights Movement at the time, she was one of the signatories to "The Treaty of Cambridge", signed in July 1963 with Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy, and state and local officials after the riot the month before.

Calling herself “a radical, a revolutionary,” she also was reportedly one of the few women leading a local civil rights protest movement at the time. For the three years in which Ms. Richardson galvanized protests against racial segregation and fought for economic justice for Cambridge’s 4,200 Black residents, she not only was a spearhead for civil rights in her community, but she also helped set off a national furor over the direction of the civil rights struggle.

Ms. Richardson not only pressured city, county, state and federal officials on racial desegregation, but she also heavily emphasized “bread and butter” issues such as housing, jobs and health care.’ #HerStory

Source: Washington Square Post
